N2  - ABSTRACT This paper examines the implications of the joint effects of insurance and taxes for the optimal corporate pension strategy. It is shown that neither the ?mini-max? nor the ?maxi-min? strategy advocated by previous authors is necessarily best in corporate pension management. In the presence of capital market imperfections, the analysis via a single-period contingent-claims model indicates that optimal corporate pension strategy in both asset-allocation and funding decisions can be a noncorner interior solution.
